NordPass homepage: https://nordpass.com/

Ordered test cases by importance
1. Critical CTA flow works correctly

Testing type: Functional testing
Priority: P1 – highest

Preconditions: User opens NordPass homepage.

Steps:

1. Open https://nordpass.com/
2. Click Sign Up
3. Return to homepage
4. Click Get a Quote
5. Click Get Personal Plan
6. Click Start Business Trial

Expected result:
Each CTA redirects to the correct relevant page. No broken links, wrong plan pages, 404 pages, or unexpected errors.

Why ranked this way:
CTA flow is the main conversion path. If users cannot sign up, request a quote, or select a plan, the homepage fails its primary business purpose.


2. Business and Personal journeys are clearly separated

Testing type: Functional / UX testing
Priority: P1 - highest

Steps:

1. Open homepage
2. Find Business section
3. Click Business-related CTA
4. Return and find Personal section
5. Click Personal-related CTA

Expected result:
Business users are taken to business/trial/quote flow. Personal users are taken to personal plan flow. Copy, navigation, and destination pages should not confuse the two user types.

Why ranked this way:
NordPass serves both business and personal users. Wrong routing could cause confusion and lost conversions.


3. Homepage is usable on mobile

Testing type: Compatibility / Responsive testing
Priority: P2 - Medium

Devices/browsers:

iPhone Safari
Android Chrome
Desktop Chrome/Edge

Steps:

1. Open homepage on mobile viewport
2. Check header, burger menu, CTAs, cards, images, and footer
3. Scroll through the full page
4. Click main CTA buttons

Expected result:
No overlapping text, broken layout, hidden CTA buttons, horizontal scrolling, or unusable menus.

Why ranked this way:
Many users will land on the homepage from mobile ads/search. A broken mobile layout directly affects conversion.


4. Homepage performance is acceptable

Testing type: Performance testing
Priority: P2 - Medium

Steps:

1. Open homepage in Chrome DevTools / Lighthouse
2. Measure loading on normal and throttled network
3. Check load time

Expected result:
Page loads quickly, main content appears without major delay, layout does not jump, images are optimized.

Why ranked this way:
Performance affects user trust, and experience. It is important, but not as critical as completely broken CTA flow.

5. Accessibility of navigation and CTA elements

Testing type: Accessibility testing
Priority: P2 - Medium

Steps:

1. Navigate the page using only keyboard
2. Check visible focus states
3. Open menu using keyboard
4. Check CTA buttons and links with screen reader
5. Verify heading structure and image alt text

Expected result:
All interactive elements are reachable and understandable. Focus order is logical. CTA buttons have meaningful accessible names.

Why ranked this way:
Accessibility is important for legal, ethical, and usability reasons. It also improves quality for all users.


